  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article titled \"Baited reconstruction with 2D template matching for high-resolution structure determination in vitro and in vivo without template bias,\" published in eLife, has garnered attention through its innovative approach to structural determination. With 15 citations already, this work reflects the significant interest and potential applications in the field. Furthermore, its early preprint version has led to three citations before formal publication, showcasing its influence at the bleeding edge of research.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research, supported by funding from the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, benefits from the strong institutional backing from prominent organizations, including the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School and the University of California, Berkeley. Such collaboration highlights the importance of this study within the biochemical and structural biology communities.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The authors' commitment to open science is particularly commendable, as evidenced by their choice to share an early version of their work as a preprint. This not only generated immediate engagement within the scientific community—reflected in three preprint citations—but it also aids in accelerating the sharing of innovative methodologies. The research focuses on a novel technique that allows high-resolution structure determination without template bias, which has implications for both vitro and in vivo applications.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the transparent availability of the peer review reports related to this work strengthens the scientific discourse, contributing to an ecosystem of trust and integrity in research. The five open peer reviews indicate rigorous scrutiny and validation by experts, reinforcing the article's credibility within the academic framework.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, this study has proven its relevance by enabling subsequent research, with 16 instances of downstream reuse noted. This demonstrates that the materials and data generated have been valuable assets for advancing further research endeavors. Thus, the article is not just a standalone contribution; rather, it serves as a foundation for future studies within structural determination, positioning itself prominently in the ongoing discourse surrounding high-resolution analysis techniques.</p>",
